s of the day enlarge brian lacorte scottsdalebased godaddy won a longstanding legal battle in phoenix that could affect similar patent infringement claims against other technology companies rpost communications ltd the los angelesbased creator of the rmail secure and certified electronic communications company that also is a patent holding company claimed godaddy’s email marketing product infringed on a broad patent regarding how email works including how email bounces back when sent to an address that is no longer active enlarge brian lacorte since rpost was threatening to sue godaddy nyse gddy the domain name registrar and small business tech provider instead decided to “take a stand” in january  and filed its own lawsuit against rpost in january  arizona federal court judge james teilborg agreed with godaddy granting a motion for summary judgment june  that said rpost’s patents were invalid and in turn the issue was moot “godaddy believes that it is important to vigorously defend itself and the industries in which it serves against meritless patent claims as was the case in this matter” said nima kelly godaddy executive vice president and general counsel in an email “we are pleased with the court’s decision showing that the asserted patent claims are invalid and should not be enforced against godaddy or anyone else” godaddy’s legal team said they thought rposts patents were invalid because they were so broad said brian lacorte a ballard spahr partner and head of the firm’s phoenix intellectual property team that represented godaddy in the case “what’s happening in these patent cases is that tech companies are saying these patents are invalid because they cover the most basic abstract concepts” lacorte said “rpost obtained patents that cover the basic functions of how email works the patents claimed to cover collecting information and tracking email to its point of destination” godaddy wasn’t seeking money just a ruling rpost counter sued for infringement and requested millions of dollars in damages lacorte said the case is the first major decision in the district of arizona on this issue following a us supreme court ruling in alice corp v cls bank international in which the court laid out new guidelines for patent eligibility “by invalidating these patents it’s a considerable ruling because it not only allows godaddy to operate but it allows other companies in the email marketing space to avoid these rpost patents” lacorte said in the past rpost has sued dozens of large tech companies including amazon adobe and ebaypaypal and has many lawsuits still making its way through court involving these patents rpost is in active litigation against tech companies such as epsilon experian strongmail docusign and symantec since godaddy is the first to actually get a judgment striking down these patents it could impact the ongoing cases lacorte said godaddy’s case was set to go to trial in august but the trial was vacated because of the judge’s decision rpost did not respond to an emailed request for comment many tech companies are taking a stand against patent infringement claims by filing suit instead of waiting to be sued lacorte said “this took a lot of perseverance and diligence” lacorte said “this costs large and small companies a lot of money at some point you stand firm and say you’re not going to pay godaddy took a stand and the judge gave good guidance” hayley ringle covers technology and startups for the phoenix business journal enlarge nima kelly is godaddys… more provided by godaddy related content godaddy buys california cloud communications company for  million godaddy pledges to hire  military vets or spouses godaddy reports revenue growth and lower net loss than a year ago home of the day sponsor listing beautiful new construction in the guard gated golf community of desert highlands see all homes of the day industries technology suggested reading featured jobs phoenix az advertising sales director phoenix business jour